There are some cool stuff you can do with Rmarkdown when you knit it to .html. Among the most cool stuff that you can do are dynamic outputs (tables and figures).

Dynamic tables

For this example were gonna use our classic Alaska fisheries data from Sea Around Us. There are probably many packages that can be used to show dynamic tables, I know datatable so will show some examples:

Normal Table

Other Options

Alaska_Data <- read.csv("data/Alaska.csv")

datatable(Alaska_Data[1:5],
          caption = 'Table 1: This is a simple caption for the table.',
          filter = 'top', options = list(
  pageLength = 5, autoWidth = TRUE
)
)

Dynamic Maps

Remember our map example of last session? Well, you can use leaflet to show dynamic maps in R-markdown! Say whaaaaaaaaaat?
